  "prompt": "How are images stored in a database?",
  "response": "Images can be stored in a database in several ways:\n\n1. Direct Storage (BLOB)\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE images (\n    id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n    image_name VARCHAR(255),\n    image_data BLOB\n)\n```\n- Stores entire image file directly in database\n- Pros: Simple, direct access\n- Cons: Large file sizes, impacts database performance\n\n2. File Path Storage\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE images (\n    id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n    image_name VARCHAR(255),\n    file_path VARCHAR(500)\n)\n```\n- Stores only file path to image on server/filesystem\n- Pros: Lightweight, better performance\n- Cons: Requires managing file system separately\n\n3. Base64 Encoding\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE images (\n    id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n    image_name VARCHAR(255),\n    base64_data TEXT\n)\n```\n- Converts image to text representation\n- Pros: Can be stored in text columns\n- Cons: Increases storage size by ~33%\n\n4. External Storage References\n- Use specialized storage services\n- Store large files in cloud storage\n- Keep reference/URL in database\n\nRecommended approach depends on:\n- Image size\n- Frequency of access\n- Performance requirements\n- Storage constraints",
